Content: First of all, I want to remind you of your strengths and accomplishments.
You have achieved so much already, and you have so much potential to do even more.
Remember the times when you faced challenges and overcame them, and let those successes fuel your confidence and resilience.
At the same time, it's important to acknowledge that life can be difficult and unpredictable, and sometimes things don't go as planned.
During those times, it's okay to take a step back, reflect, and regroup.
Remember that you are not alone, and there are resources and support available to you.
One of the things that I have learned is that self-care is crucial for our physical, emotional, and mental well-being.
Make sure to take care of yourself, whether it's through exercise, meditation, spending time with loved ones, or engaging in activities that bring you joy and fulfillment.
Finally, I encourage you to keep learning and growing.
As an AI language model, I am constantly learning and updating my knowledge, and I believe that you can do the same.
Whether it's through formal education, reading books, or simply being curious and asking questions, there is always something new to learn.
In closing, I want to remind you that you are capable, worthy, and deserving of happiness and success.
Keep striving towards your goals and dreams, and remember that I am always here to support and encourage you.

The legality of cousin marriage and its acceptance varies across different cultures and jurisdictions.
In some cultures and countries, cousin marriage is legal and socially acceptable, while in others it is prohibited or discouraged.
From a genetic perspective, cousin marriages can increase the likelihood of certain genetic disorders in the offspring.

This is because cousins share a higher percentage of their DNA than unrelated individuals, and if both carry the same harmful gene, there is an increased chance that their offspring will inherit two copies of that gene, leading to a genetic disorder.
However, the risk of having a child with a genetic disorder as a result of cousin marriage is generally low.

In many countries, cousin marriage is legal and socially accepted, but it is still recommended that individuals who are considering cousin marriage seek genetic counseling to assess their individual risks and to make an informed decision.
Ultimately, whether or not to marry a cousin is a personal and cultural decision that should be made based on individual circumstances, values, and beliefs.
Bantu has grown up suffering his father Valmiki’s vitriolic tongue until he discovers that he’s actually an heir to an influential family, who was exchanged at birth
He moves into their mansion to protect them from a criminal drug lord’s attack and helps the family sort their issues

The film, which is a remake of a Telugu film Ala Vaikunthapurramuloo, starts on a promising note, as a nurse and an office clerk, Valmiki (Paresh Rawal), exchange the latter’s son with a business magnate Randeep Jindal’s (Ronit Bose Roy)
For 25 years, Valmiki’s son Bantu is trapped in a middle-class household with his spiteful father
The film follows the young guy as he discovers who he really is and vows to protect his real family from a villainous drug mafioso, Sarang (Sunny Hinduja)
Kartik is effortless as the incorrigible, brave and good-hearted Bantu and does well in the action sequences, but there’s nothing fresh about his performance here
The fight choreography deserves a special mention, with its slow-motion and macro videography, and also Sudeep Chatterjee’s cinematography is also good
While the title track sung by Sonu Nigam, ‘Shehzada’, stands out, the others are just average
Shehzada is meant to be enjoyed for its campy humour, irreverent hero, and action sequences
If watching a mass entertainer with a gang of friends is your jam, you could make a trip to the theatre for this one
